title: Coffee Break: How Nature Supports Southern Arizonaâ€™s Economy
description:
People from all over the world come to southern Arizona to experience the great outdoors, recreate, and just be among the areaâ€™s scenic landscapes and wildlife. But how much is that worth, and what are the costs if itâ€™s lost? 

Join Sky Island Alliance for our next virtual Coffee Break on June 12 at 9:30 a.m. Weâ€™ll be joined by Borderlands Restoration Network board member Chuck Klingenstein, who will share results from the first [Nature-Based Restorative Economy study](https://santacruzcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Santa-Cruz-County-NBRE-Full-Report.pdf) in Santa Cruz County, commissioned by the community and conducted by the University of Arizona. 

This in-depth study looked at the many benefits nature provides to our economy in southern Arizona through ecotourism, conservation, and other activities. SIA Executive Director Louise Misztal will also provide updates on South32â€™s Hermosa Mine in the Patagonia Mountains and how you can speak up for this natural gem that supports our well-being and economy by taking action during the current comment period on the mineâ€™s impacts.

**More Background**

The Nature-Based Restorative Economy study was conducted by the University of Arizona, and it was commissioned by the Town of Patagonia, Sky Island Tourism Association, Borderlands Restoration Network, Tucson Bird Alliance, The Nature Conservancy, Patagonia Area Resource Alliance, and Sky Island Alliance, as well as other organizations, businesses, and individuals active in Santa Cruz County, Arizona. The purpose of the study was to understand the components of the nature-based restorative economy in Santa Cruz County by using traditional economic modeling. The study also separated out these components, since the nature-based restorative economy isnâ€™t currently a defined sector in government data sets.

Specific Study Goals

- To define the components of the nature-based restorative economy in Santa Cruz County and collect data on its contribution to the overall economy. This was the first time this has been done.

- To measure the growth of the nature-based restorative economy sector by collecting baseline data for future comparison.

- To inform elected officials and other policymakers, businesses, nonprofits, and the public about the current economic impacts and potential opportunities for growth afforded by the nature-based restorative economy in Santa Cruz County.
